Final Project: Crime Rate in Montgomery County, MD.¶

Introduction¶

Crime happen regularly in our lives, and therefore, it is essential to know about the criminal activity in the US to carry out security estimations. To that reason, this tutorial presents a profound examination on crime reports in a much smaller region - Montgomery County, MD from 2016 to present. In order to examine the dataset, this tutorial incorporates four fundamental parts. The initial stage will implement information fetching and tidying. Thereafter, the subsequent part will exhibit how to investigate the given information and perform data visuzliation. The third part will then continue the second section by performing hypothesis testing. Lastly, the conclusion section will communicate the insights attained by the previous stages.

Required Tools & Data¶

We will be using Jupyter Notebook as the coding platform. Additionally we will be using the following libraries to conduct the data fetching, analysis, visulation, and testing:

  • pandas
  • numpy
  • statsmodel
  • matplotlib
  • folium

For the dataset, the crime records for Montgomery County, MD can be retrived at https://data.montgomerycountymd.gov/Public-Safety/Crime/icn6-v9z3

PART 1: Data Fetching & Tidying¶

In order to begin the data analysis process, the first thing we need to do is download the dataset as CSV(comma-separated value) from the link above. The file can be named anything;for this tutorial it is named dataset.csv. Then, we load the CSV file into a pandas dataframe to enable further analysis. To do this, we will use Pandas.read_csv().

In [ ]:
# Import required modules.
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import statsmodels.api as api
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import folium as fo
import warnings
from statsmodels.formula.api import ols as st

# We use this to supress any warnings.
warnings.filterwarnings('ignore')

# Initalize a pandas dataframe, named data, from content in our CSV file.
data = pd.read_csv("dataset.csv", dtype=object)

1.1: Data Overview¶

The dataset is consists of 295,000 rows, each with appromixtely 30 columns that provide crucial information like: crime type, location, time, agency and etc. Out of these 30 colmuns we will be using the following for the rest of our tutorial:

  • City
  • State
  • Crime name 1
  • Crime name 2
  • Victims
  • Longitude
  • Latitude
  • Start_Date_Time
  • End_Date_Time

1.2: Data Tidying¶

As mentioned above the dataset contains a lot of unwanted columns. Therefore, we will need remove any unwnated columns and empty/invalid rows to prevent errors. Additonally we will try to parse the date_time columns to serperate enable better analysis of crime vs time.

In [ ]:
# Drop unwanted columns.
data = data.drop('Offence Code', 1)
data = data.drop('CR Number', 1)
data = data.drop('Dispatch Date / Time', 1)
data = data.drop('NIBRS Code', 1)
data = data.drop('Sector', 1)
data = data.drop('Beat', 1)
data = data.drop('PRA', 1)

# Delete rows with N/A and empty colmuns in dataset.
data = data.dropna(subset=["Latitude"])
data = data.dropna(subset=["Longitude"])
data = data.dropna(subset=["Crime Name1"])
data = data.dropna(subset=["Crime Name2"])
data = data.dropna(subset=["Start_Date_Time"])
data = data.dropna(subset=["End_Date_Time"])

# Parse date_time to extract rows.
data['year'] = pd.DatetimeIndex(data['Start_Date_Time']).year

Part 2: Data Analysis & Visualization¶

At this point, our data is ready to analyze. In this part, we would like to visualize the data we just cleaned up with some plots and map in order to portray and explain the trend of crimes to the audience. We will also generate statistical data for to get better clarity. We are interested in analyzing crime rates in Montogomery County, MD, and so we will use compare and cotnrast the following types for the rest of the tutorial: Motor Vehicle Theft, Drug Violation, Assault, and Vandalism.

2.1: Motor Vehicle Theft¶

This is relatively simple. To achieve our objective all we need to do is use Pandas.loc() to filter the rows that are related to car theft and Pandas.groupby() to group the fitered datset by year so that we can visualize it using matplotlib.

In [ ]:
# Extract all rows in the dataset that are related to vehicle theft.
theft_data = data.loc[data['Crime Name2'] == 'Motor Vehicle Theft']

# Use groupby and count functions to count thefts in a year.
theft_data_by_year = theft_data.copy().groupby(theft_data['year'], as_index=True, group_keys=True).count()
theft_data_count = theft_data_by_year[['Incident ID']].reset_index()
theft_data_count = theft_data_count.rename(index=str, columns={'Incident ID' : 'Count'})
print(theft_data_count)

# Let's plot!! Put data in plot and label the graph accordingly.
plt.plot(theft_data_count['year'], theft_data_count['Count'], color='red')
plt.title('Number of Auto mobile thefts Vs Year')
plt.xlabel('Year')
plt.ylabel('Number of Motor Vehicle Thefts')

plt.show()

   year  Count
0  2016    455
1  2017    697
2  2018    629
3  2019    615
4  2020    885
5  2021   1039
6  2022    316

From the plot above, it is observed that the number of theft seems to have decreased by year in recent years. The number of car thefts reached maximum in the period from 2019 to 2021. After that, the number seems to be decreasing and has acehived a new low of 316 (the smallest yet) in 2022. Since the graphs is scattered across all years, it is diffcult to observe some kind of trend therefore we will need to perform further analysis in later steps to gain more clarity. Let's create some small statistical data on it as well.

In [ ]:
theft_mean = theft_data_count['Count'].mean()
theft_std = theft_data_count['Count'].std()
print("Mean: " + str(theft_mean) + " theft/year")
print("Standard Deviation: " + str(theft_std))

Mean: 662.2857142857143 theft/year
Standard Deviation: 244.589938663139

2.3: Assault¶

Like 2.2, this is also relatively simple. To achieve our objective all we need to do is use Pandas.loc() to filter the rows that are related to assault and Pandas.groupby() to group the fitered datset by year so that we can visualize it using matplotlib. Please note that assault herein refers to 'simple assault', meaning a person commits a simple assault if he attempts, to put another in fear of imminent serious bodily injury and not necessarily commits the deed.

Combine part 2¶

Now that we have individaully filter and graphed various criminal activities reported in Montgomery, MD by year; let's combine each subplot so that we can draw conclusion amongst each types of incident and possible find some trend that explains the graphs above. Although we have obsereved non-trendy graphs eariler on, we can observe that the combined graph will showcase a downward trend in recents years (2021-2022).

In [ ]:
# Let's plot!! Put data in plot and label the graph accordingly.
plt.plot(theft_data_count['year'], theft_data_count['Count'], label ='theft')
plt.plot(drug_data_count['year'], drug_data_count['Count'], label ='drug')
plt.plot(as_data_count['year'], as_data_count['Count'], label ='assault')
plt.plot(vand_data_count['year'], vand_data_count['Count'], label ='vandalism')
plt.ylabel('Total Count')
plt.xlabel('Year')
plt.title('Combined graph Vs Year')
plt.legend(bbox_to_anchor=(1.1, 1.05))
plt.show()

Based on the graph above we can concur that our hypothesis above was partially correct. We can observe that the graph doesn't have a noticeable trend however it has some pattern that are intersting. For example, there is been a increase in crime from 2016 to 2017 and a decrease between 2021 and 2022. This warrants further study into the topic? Has is there some outside factor that has this effect? Will we find a similar trend for all other crime types?

Below is a interactive map, created using Folium, that pinpoints the location of each type of incident in the county based on latitude and longitude and year. Since the dataset is large we have restricted the amount of rows we are going to plot to avoid congestion. You can learn more about the api at: https://python-visualization.github.io/folium/.

This the color key followed for year:

  • 2016: Red
  • 2017: Blue
  • 2018: Green
  • 2019: Pink
  • 2020: Purple
  • 2021: Orange
  • 2022: Gray

Motor Vehicle Theft Map¶

In [ ]:
# Create a Folium map centered at Montogomery County, MD.
map_osm = fo.Map(location=[39.15, -77.24], zoom_start=13)

# Get the first 200 rows to plot. Plotting everything will congest the map.
theft_sub = theft_data.head(200)
theft_data_2016 = theft_sub.loc[data['year'] == 2016]
theft_data_2017 = theft_sub.loc[data['year'] == 2017]
theft_data_2018 = theft_sub.loc[data['year'] == 2018]
theft_data_2019 = theft_sub.loc[data['year'] == 2019]
theft_data_2020 = theft_sub.loc[data['year'] == 2020]
theft_data_2021 = theft_sub.loc[data['year'] == 2021]
theft_data_2022 = theft_sub.loc[data['year'] == 2022]

# For each sub dataset above plot them with a unique color based on year. The Folium.Marker() method places a pin at a given lat. and long.
# and can color each pin uniquely. 
for index, incident in theft_data_2016.iterrows():
    fo.Marker(location=[incident["Latitude"], incident["Longitude"]],icon=fo.Icon(color='red')).add_to(map_osm)
for index, incident in theft_data_2017.iterrows():
    fo.Marker(location=[incident["Latitude"], incident["Longitude"]],icon=fo.Icon(color='blue')).add_to(map_osm)
for index, incident in theft_data_2018.iterrows():
    fo.Marker(location=[incident["Latitude"], incident["Longitude"]],icon=fo.Icon(color='green')).add_to(map_osm)
for index, incident in theft_data_2019.iterrows():
    fo.Marker(location=[incident["Latitude"], incident["Longitude"]],icon=fo.Icon(color='pink')).add_to(map_osm)
for index, incident in theft_data_2020.iterrows():
    fo.Marker(location=[incident["Latitude"], incident["Longitude"]],icon=fo.Icon(color='purple')).add_to(map_osm)
for index, incident in theft_data_2021.iterrows():
    fo.Marker(location=[incident["Latitude"], incident["Longitude"]],icon=fo.Icon(color='orange')).add_to(map_osm)
for index, incident in theft_data_2022.iterrows():
    fo.Marker(location=[incident["Latitude"], incident["Longitude"]],icon=fo.Icon(color='gray')).add_to(map_osm)

PART 3: Hypothesis Testing¶

Now that we have our analysis done we can start doing linear regression and start testing our hypothesis. When doing a linear regression, we're taking data that is already there and predicting future data base on the patterns of the data we already have. We are going to take a linear regression of all four types however for the sake of hypothesis testing we wont't be performing tests on all four crime types. Note testing all four crime types will make this tutorial very long and hard to follow through; however you can do it if you are intestered. Simply follow the steps below to generate and test your own hypothesis.

3.1: Linear Regression¶

This process is relatively simple. Essentially we just need to convert our data into lists that can be passed into the Numpy.polyfit() function to get a linear regression. After that we will just plot the regression obtained using matplotlib. You can learn more about Numpy at: https://numpy.org.

In [ ]:
# Extract the required theft data from pandas dataframe into a list so that they can be
# passed into the polyfit function.
count_arr = []
count_arr.extend(theft_data_count['Count'].to_numpy().tolist())
year_arr = []
year_arr.extend(theft_data_count['year'].to_numpy().tolist())

# Get the regression line function using numpy.polyfit().
func = np.polyfit(year_arr, count_arr, 1)
regline_coords = [func[0] * i + func[1] for i in year_arr]
 
# Plot the regression line coordinates.
plt.plot(theft_data_count['year'], theft_data_count['Count'], color='red', label='Motor Vehicle Theft')
plt.plot(year_arr,regline_coords, 'b')
plt.ylabel('Number of Motor Vehicle Thefts')
plt.xlabel('Year')
plt.title('Linear Regression of Auto mobile thefts Vs Year')
plt.legend(bbox_to_anchor=(1.1, 1.05))
plt.show()

Let's see if we can use hypothesis testing to get some more clarification, although in my opinion I think this is mere co-incidence and not a mathematical correlation.

3.2: Hypothesis Testing¶

For this process we will be using statsmodel to generate a statistical regression model for both simple assault and vandalisms. After our regression is completed we will perfom F-Tests to verify whether there exists a correlation between simple assaults and vandalism or it's just a coincidence. For our purposes we will be using statsmodel.anova to perform our F-Test. Note, this is not the only way to perform F-Tests. More information can be foung at: https://www.statsmodels.org/stable/index.html.

In [ ]:
# Create a regression using statsmodel.fit() and as_data_count dataset.

print("Vandalism Regression.")
print(vand_reg.summary())

Part 4: Conclusion¶

The purpose of this study is to gain insight on the crime rates in Montogomery County, MD. As a resident of the county, it is very important for me to be aware of the activities going around my residents. Although, reading some wiki-page can give a few facts it is still not effective. Rather trends and distribution can be effectively analyzed and communicated using data science. Our tutorial is an example of how we can use data science to help the audience be more aware about what is happening in our lives and around us. This tutorial serves not only to teach the audience about data science and its importance but also provide some mathematical insight into the crimes happeneing around us. Note, this regression models can be used to predict/estimate future values of each activities as well.

Based on the dataset that we obtained from opendata.maryland.gov, we can conclude that the crime rates for motor vehicle theft, vandalism, drug violations and assault has decresed severly in Montgomery County, MD, in the past years. We notice that there was a influx of these activties in early 2016 to late 2017, however as the years progressed the recorded incidents hit a new low in 2022. From this we can conclude that crime has been decreasing in the county in recent years and the region is becoming amuch more safer place. While this is great news, it raises the question on what factors were responsible for such change? Since we were not able to find a correlation between any of our parsed dataframe, is it possible that something similar can be found for the rest of our open soruce dataset? Is is probable to assume that cirmes would hit a new low in the next few years or would it increase back again?

The dataset that we used contains a lot of information, not just the amount of recorded incidents or the date_time, but also the information of victims. Therefore we encourge the readers, if interested, to use the various data columsn to start a experiment of their own or even contiue this tutorial to answer some of the question listed above. With the tools that we used above, readers can perform more complex analysis and visualiztions with the rest of the open source data. The audience can also experiment with data of their liking since this the steps covered in this tutorial are generic and can be applied to any dataset for basic analysis.
